r': Read mode</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ 'w': Write mode (creates new file or overwrites)</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ 'a': Append mode (adds content without deleting existing data)</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ 'rb', 'wb': Binary modes for non-text files</p>    <p>Example:</p>    <p><code>file = open("example.txt", "r")  # Opens the file in read mode</code></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Reading Files</strong></p>    <p>Python provides multiple ways to read file contents:</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>.read()</code>: Reads the entire file</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>.readline()</code>: Reads a single line at a time</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>.readlines()</code>: Reads all lines and returns a list</p>    <p>Example:</p>    <p><code>with open("example.txt", "r") as file:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data = file.read()<br>print(data)</code></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Writing & Appending to Files</strong></p>    <p>Writing is essential for saving data, like storing a user‚Äôs progress or keeping a record.</p>    <p><code>write()</code> overwrites content, while <code>append()</code> adds new content without deleting.</p>    <p>Example:</p>    <p><code>with open("output.txt", "w") as file:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;file.write("Hello, Python!")</code></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Closing Files</strong></p>    <p>Files should be closed after processing to release system resources.</p>    <p>Using Python‚Äôs <code>with</code> statement automatically handles closing:</p>    <p><code>with open("example.txt", "r") as file:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data = file.read()<br># File is automatically closed after this block</code></p>  </article></section>    </div>  </div></section>   <!-- ====== Introduction to exceptions handling in python====== --><section id="python-exceptions-handling" style="    display: flex;    justify-content: center;    padding: 4rem 2rem;    background-image: url('images/water\ fall.jpg');    background-size: cover;       /* Makes image cover the section */    background-position: center;  /* Centers the image */    background-repeat: no-repeat; /* Prevent tiling */    background-attachment: scroll; /* Optional, prevents fixed zoom */">  <div style="      max-width: 900px;       width: 100%;       background-color: rgb(189, 35, 15);       border-radius: 15px;       box-shadow: 0 8px 20px rgba(247, 238, 238, 0.2);       overflow: hidden;       text-align: center;       padding: 2rem;">    <!-- Image at top of the card -->    <div style="        width: 100%;         height: 300px;         background-image: url('images/exceptions\ handling.PNG');         background-size: cover;         background-position: center;         border-radius: 10px;">    </div>    <!-- Content under image -->    <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">      <h2 style="margin-bottom: 2rem; color: #f0eeee;"><b>exceptions handling</b></h2><section>  <article>    <p>‚ö†Ô∏è <strong>Exception Handling</strong> (1.5 hours)</p>    <p>Errors happen! To make sure your programs are error-proof and user-friendly, Python provides <strong>Exception Handling</strong>. It‚Äôs the art of catching errors and handling them gracefully.</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Basic Structure of try-except Blocks</strong></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>try:</code> Runs code that might throw an error.</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>except:</code> Catches the error, allowing you to respond without crashing.</p>    <p>Example:</p>    <p><code>try:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;with open("nonexistent.txt", "r") as file:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data = file.read()<br>except FileNotFoundError:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;print("File not found. Please check the filename.")</code></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Advanced Error Handling with finally and Custom Errors</strong></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <code>finally:</code> Runs no matter what, often used to clean up (like closing a file).</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Custom Errors:</strong> Create custom exceptions for special cases (e.g., <code>EmptyFileError</code>).</p>    <p>Example with <code>finally</code>:</p>    <p><code>try:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;file = open("sample.txt", "r")<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data = file.read()<br>except FileNotFoundError:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;print("File not found.")<br>finally:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;file.close()</code></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ <strong>Best Practices</strong></p>    <p>‚Ä¢ Use <code>with</code> for file handling: auto-close files, preventing potential leaks.</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ Check file existence before reading/writing to avoid crashes.</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ Handle specific exceptions over general ones (e.g., <code>FileNotFoundError</code> instead of <code>Exception</code>).</p>    <p>‚Ä¢ Document error messages clearly for easier debugging and user support.</p>  </article></section>      <!-- Buttons -->      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">        <a href="DOCUMENTS PDF/PYTHON COMPLETE NOTES WITH TAWFIQ/FILE HANDLING&EXCEPTION IN PYTHON 4/EXCEPTION HANDLING IN PYTHON.pdf" download class="card-link">Download Notes</a>      </div>    </div>  </div></section>   <!-- ====== FOOTER ====== -->  <footer id="footer">    <p>¬© 2025 Coding with Tawfiq. All rights reserved.</p>  </footer>